title: Seriously impressed! Glass shine all the way around!
text:
2nd day update:
See last 2 pictures. It rained and blew a ton of dust the night after the full detail. (Of course) the first is the dirty, the last picture is after a quick rinse and dry. Although it didn't completely repell the rain it came off super ez. And shined up like it never happened with minimal effort. Crazy how good this works.
Used this for the first time today. Used as a wax to clean after doing an at home pressure wash with my foam cannon. Unfortunately I have very hard water at my house so it's nearly impossible to get it perfectly dry. There is almost always hard water spots.
I decided to try this as a finishing product and I could not believe how great it works. It's literally a mirror finish all the way around. Every surface plastic, chrome, rims and paint all shine very easily.
I used about a quarter of a bottle to detail a 2021 silverado z71 from front to back including the inside of the door trim and every surface including the external glass. Pretty impressive.
TIPS:
I used a micro fiber detailing sponge as the wet rub and it worked well.
Make sure whatever you use for the wet wipes portion stays damp. If it gets too dry it is A LOT more work. Comes off really easier if you keep the cloth/sponge damp. Not dripping wet, just hand squeeze dry it and that's about perfect.
You will notice a build up in the dry cloth, I used 2 micro fiber clothes on the body and trim and a third for the rims. Even though I used the same wet sponge for the whole truck.
The dry cloth needs to be clean to get the best shine.
Last tip, if you aren't sure whether or not you have done a surface gently wipe a micro fiber on it. If it's been armored it will slide without resistance. If not, it will feel much different.

Highly recommend this product!

It has a nice strong magnet on the bottom to easily adhere to the top of your car or any metal that magnets work on.  Batteries were so easy to change.  The bottom unscrews to reveal the battery compartment.  It appears to be reasonably well made; not made of cheap, thin plastic that will break soon.  Although it appears to be mostly plastic, it is good quality.  Well worth the price for your safety.  I can't find anything to criticize with this item.  It is simple, well made and it works! title: Nice Covers, but only work for certain types of seats
text: These are very colorful and seem to be durable and well made.  They seem to fit the seats snugly.  At first I thought they weren't big enough, but they stretch, so they fit firmly and won't be loosening up.  The fact that they stretch also probably makes them compatible with slightly different sized seats.  I was disappointed that I could not use these with the seats in my car because my seats have an arm rest attached to the side of the back of the seat.  If arm rests are separate, these should work for you, but if the arm rest is part of the seat, there is no way to work around it.  Another problem is that if ever want to adjust your headrests, if you have adjustable ones as I do, the seat cover goes over the head rest and you can't get to the button to adjust it.  We never adjust our headrests and most people probably don't, so probably wouldn't be a big issue.  A final little issue is that the backs of my seats have a pocket in them for use of the passengers in the back.  The seat covers cover that pocket, so you can't get to it.  If you don't use the pockets in the back of your seats or don't have them, that won't be a problem.  Really nice seat covers, but will only work with a certain type of bucket seat.  Also there is a warning on the package that they contain material that is known in California to cause cancer, but that wouldn't be a concern to me, as I wouldn't be making any direct contact with the material and have no children or pets that would be riding on the seats.  If you often wear shorts or sleeveless shirts, you might not want your skin touching them repeatedly, because of the cancer warning.  If you don't, I wouldn't worry about it and I wouldn't hesitate to use these, if they would fit my seats.

title: Nice looking flagpole
text:
All in all it seems like a good quality flag pole. We will see later how the flag itself holds up to the constant flapping while I’m riding.
A lot of people have complained how either the flag eventually slips right off the end, or the top part unscrews and they lose both it and the flag.
There are a couple of easy solutions if you take the time to actually think about it. As far as the flag, slipping off after you screw the top piece on, you could add some stitching to make it really snugged on the pole, so it will not slip off.
An easier way is to simply get a flat washer that’s approximately the same diameter as the threaded part and put it on there before screwing the top piece on. That way there is no way the flag could slip off.
Most people that have lost that top piece, obviously didn’t think to tighten it with pliers.
I gripped the top piece and the pole with two pair of pliers, using a piece of cloth so the teeth wouldn’t tear up the chrome, and snugged it down.
It’s definitely not coming off. If you want to make doubly sure you could always put a small, very small amount of Loctite on there, but I personally wouldn’t do that. If you ever have to change out the flag, it would be very difficult to undo it without damaging the chrome.

The manufacturer of this flag pole would be smart if they simply put a flat surface on two sides of the top piece so you could use an open end wrench to tighten it down. They could also flare out the bottom of the top piece, so a flag would not be able to get past it.

text:

You can’t beat the price, of 6 quarts for around $35. You can do three oil changes for $70 whereas with Golden Spectro or Honda’s blend, you would pay around $150, not counting the oil filter. If you change your oil every 5000 miles, which is perfectly acceptable, you are definitely getting your moneys worth.
Those who change their motorcycle oil every 3000 miles are wasting money, especially if they use the more expensive synthetic or semi-synthetic oil’s.

title: Impressive!
text: I recently bought an SUV. My previous car was a mini-van. It didn't take very long for me to figure out that I needed something like this for my trips to the grocery. In my van, there was a deep well where my groceries would go and they couldn't roll around all over the car. With my SUV, I keep the 3rd row seat down for a larger cargo space and my groceries would roll all over! I have 2 different trunk organizer back there and they help tremendously. I decided I wanted a 3rd one. This one is definitely the best! If I had gotten this one first, I still probably would have gotten at least one more, but I think 2 would have been suffice. This one is the longest of the three units. It's also the sturdiest. It's versatile regarding the dividers inside. The handles are sturdy. Overall, I find this to be an impressive trunk organizer.

title: Better Than Exptected!
text: This trunk organizer is better than expected. The size is great! There's lots of room for items and it keeps things from rolling around in the back of my SUV. The dividers are attached with Velcro, so you have the flexibility to take them out or rearrange them. There are pockets on the side. There's a removable lid. My favorite feature is the sturdy metal handles! That makes it easy to transport the entire unit if desired. I am very impressed with this organizer and I'm so glad I have it!

title: Prevents Items from Falling Between the Seats

It's too narrow to reach down and grabbed the dropped items. I have put these in that space. They're squished pretty closely, but they can accommodate a phone. Because of the thinness, I can't really use it for storing items, but it does prevent items from falling down in between the seats. The pockets are very well made and look very nice. A wider gap would allow you to utilize it more, but I am happy to be able to keep my phone from accidental drops while driving!

title: Great Organizer!

title: Great Idea!
text: I think coasters for the car is a great idea! It allows you to add some color to the interior of your car and it helps with sweaty cups! I drive a 2010 Toyota Sienna. Over the years, my cup holders have gotten a bit gross. I clean them out regularly, but they don't look pristine any more. The simple addition of these coasters detracts from all that! Plus, I'm not getting little puddles of liquid. This set has 4 coasters. There are 2 of each design. I kind of wish that all 4 were the same, but that's just a personal preference. My van has 4 cup holders in the console - 2 in the front part and 2 in the back part for the middle seats to access. A sedan probably only has 2 cup holders in the front, so it's not an issue. title: Quick Reading

title: Heavy Duty
text: My 19 year old daughter recently inherited grandma's car. The car was well maintained, but we were surprised that Grandma didn't have any jumper cables in the trunk. We wanted our daughter to be prepared, so I ordered this. When it arrived, I was caught off guard with how heavy it was. I wasn't expecting that at all. Then after handling, you can immediately tell the difference between these cables and others. They are truly heavy duty. The very day they arrived, my daughter went to her car to put new floor mats inside. The door wasn't opening with the key fob, so she had to insert the key into the lock. Then it was discovered that the car battery was dead. Lucky for me, this gave me the perfect opportunity to try these out. They worked as they should and as expected. The car is a 2012 Honda Civic. The reader indicated that it wasn't an issue with the alternator., which was good. Our daughter got to learn first hand how to jump start her car. When the car was up and running again, we discovered that she had left one of the overhead lights on, so of course, we had to point that out to her so she would be aware of that in the future. We were able to charge the battery overnight. All is good. The cables come with a storage bag, but it was nearly impossible to get them back in it. In fact, I don't think I did get them in properly. I guess I was thinking that I would do that later. The set included a flashlight and a pair of gloves, too. The flashlight doesn't come with batteries and it was cracked, so we'll probably just give her a different one. We compared the cables with the ones in my husband's car and they are significantly heavier, longer, and thicker. I would definitely recommend these!

title: Well....
text: My daughter has recently gotten her first car. I thought this would be great for her to have. Well......it's got a lot of stuff in it, but the items are pretty basic and some of them are poor quality. The kit comes in a storage bag. There are jumper cables, a safety vest, tire pressure gauge, safety triangle, ice scraper, screwdriver, tape, whistle and more. The safety vest is pretty light weight and cheap, but it works and will definitely draw attention to you if you were out changing a tire. The whistle is sturdy and decent. The safety triangle is a much better option than road flares, but it's wobbly. The rain poncho is cheap and probably only a one time use. The snow shovel is really more like an ice scraper. The tow hook is not very sturdy and it's questionable as to how strong it would be in use. Overall, it's got a lot of stuff, but it might be better to purchase better quality items that you will feel confident that will work in an emergency. We plan to do that for our daughter.

title: Nice Plate Frame!
text: I have never had a frame on my license plate before, but I recently got a new tag that has a lot of white space on it. It looks lost on my minivan. The frame makes a huge difference on how it looks. This was very easy to install. It's silicone and comes with everything you need to install it on your vehicle, even disposable gloves! The frame is simple and doesn't block any of the pertinent information that needs to be visible. And since it's silicone, it doesn't make any noise when going over bumps! title: Worked Well on One of Our Cars
text: My husband's license plate got all bent up in a car wash recently. I thought this would help prevent that from happening again. He drives a Honda Civic. We started to install it with the holes at the top, but that covered up the expiration date and county. My husband didn't want to get a ticket for that. So we put it up the other way with the holes at the bottom. That worked really well. The license plate is secured with screws at the top and the frame is secured at the bottom. It came with tops to cover the screws so it's all uniform looking. We planned to put the other frame on our son's car. His plate has been bent up, too. (We think our state has been using really cheap, thin metal for tags!) Unfortunately, we couldn't use it on his car. He drives a Toyota Prius. The car doesn't have screw holes at the bottom, only at the top of where the plate goes. We tried my Toyota Sienna next. Same problem. Only top holes in my car, as well. The frame works well on some cars! If you don't want information covered by the frame and use it the way we did, make sure your car can do that!

title: Easy to Set Up!
text: We recently had a trailer hitch installed on my Toyota Sienna mini van. We thought this cargo rack could come in handy, especially with our daughter moving to college this fall. From out of the box, it took my husband less than 20 minutes to assemble. He used a socket set instead of the tools provided, which he recommends to anyone getting this. Once it was put together, it didn't take long to set it up on the van's hitch. It does require a wrench for installing it on the hitch, so make sure you take one with you just in case. There's a sleeve inside the bar that attaches to the hitch. The first time we tried hooking it up, the sleeve had slipped out a little, so we could not get the bolt to screw in because the threads weren't lined up properly. Once we discovered that, we were more careful when sliding it on to the hitch so the sleeve wouldn't slide out and we were able to get it in correctly. The hitch we have is close to the ground. This angles up a little so it leaves adequate clearance. My husband drove it around the neighborhood a few times and didn't notice any rattling or other noises, and it seemed to drive smoothly. The rack is pretty sturdy and well made. It did get scratched up a little during assembly though. Overall, we're quite pleased with it and better yet, we don't think we'll need to rent a trailer to move our daughter into her dorm. I think between this and the space in the van, we'll be good.

text:
I got tired of those "stick" tire pressure gauges breaking and of wondering whether they're accurate or not. For less than ten bucks this is good:

PROS: Heavy duty; either side of the connector works so can use at different angles; checked it against a friend's expensive air compressor gauge and it's accurate; bleeder valve lets out air down to PSI you want; round part is encased in rubber.

CONS: Turns a one-handed job (with the stick gauge) into a two-handed job; takes up more space in a glove compartment.

Press the connector onto the tire and it pressurizes the gauge to the PSI. Then the gauge holds the reading until you press the bleeder valve on the side. I fill my tires to ~35 PSI on a 12-volt portable air compressor, then use this and bleed it down to 30. Easy every time.

title: Perfect Fit, Easy to Manage
text:
We purchased two sets of front floor liners, one for a Ford Escape and the other for a Jeep Patriot. The installation in the Jeep turned out to be much more satisfactory for the following reasons: (1) the liners are much more FLEXIBLE than the ones we received for the Escape; and (2) the Jeep uses a simple hook to hold the driver's side carpet in place. The design of the liner on the driver's side easily accommodates the hook. (See my companion review of the liners for a Ford Escape.)

Because of the flexibility of the liners and the interior design of the Jeep, it appears that the liners will be easily removable should they contain liquid or debris. They will readily go "straight up and out" of the vehicle should the need arise.

The installation of the liners in the Jeep turned out to be a much more satisfying experience than for the Escape. The liners for the Jeep give a much better measure of this product. You should be very happy, as we are, if you buy these liners for your Jeep Patriot!

title: Keeps Your Vehicle Clean (Updated June 2013)
text:
These liners cover the front carpet for both the driver and passenger sides. They are very sturdy and help to trap whatever would have wound up on your interior carpeting. They fit snugly. All very good so far.

The Ford Escape has two grommets (plastic) that normally hold the carpet in place. To install the liners, you must remove the carpet, which is easy to do. This leaves the two grommets exposed. Now the liner does have grommet holes which are supposed to match up with and fit over the two grommets. This is where matters go slightly awry: the liners that I received for the Escape are VERY stiff, so it is not very easy to position the liner holes over the grommets -- esp. the grommet farther in. I was not able to get the grommets into the holes of the liner. The holes seem a tad small. It does not seem to matter, because the liner fits very snugly and does not seem to move around at all. Since there are no grommets on the passenger front carpeting, there is no issue on the passenger side.

Because the liners I received are so stiff, I am not quite sure how easy it will be to lift the liners out and dispose of any liquid that might accumulate (e.g. snow, coffee spills, and the like). There is the possibility that in trying to remove these liners, the liquid could wind up all over the remaining layer of carpet. It does not seem that the liners will easily go "straight up and out" because of the inside dimensions of the Escape and the size of the liners.

All in all I am glad we bought them, because they are better than the alternative -- messy carpets. The liners are well made and they look good in the vehicle. I just wish they were a bit more flexible for the reasons outlined above.

title: Not small enough for me...
text:
Sadly, I have super tiny hands, and that makes it incredibly difficult to find proper motorcycle gloves that fit and offer good protection. I got a pair of XS gloves and they were still too big. However, they are the closest I've come to fitting me properly from any gloves I've gotten, so I will give a star for that. The palms are fine, but the fingertips are way too long.

Sizing apart, the quality of the gloves are no better than you'd expect from cheap gloves. Sadly due to the sizing issue, it's hard to find the right size in any quality so I try to make due with what I can get. The knuckles are hardened, but not with that hard rubberized material other high quality gloves have. The rest of the glove is rather thin but flexible. While it's nice to have that extra mobility, I wouldn't trust these in a high speed fall. These would fall apart. For driving around town, these should be more than enough. And with the touch phone fingertips, it can be pretty convenient when quickly checking something on your phone.

These are the gloves I'm using now, and so far with light use, they have been holding up just fine. I'll update if anything comes up over time.
